org.springframework.cloud.contract.spec.Contract.make { request { // (1) method 'PUT' // (2) url '/fraudcheck' // (3) body([ // (4) "client.id": $(regex('[0-9]{10}')), loanAmount: 99999 ]) headers { // (5) contentType('application/json') } } response { // (6) status 200 // (7) body([ // (8) fraudCheckStatus: "FRAUD", "rejection.reason": "Amount too high" ]) headers { // (9) contentType('application/json') } } }
/* From the Consumer perspective, when shooting a request in the integration test:
(1) - If the consumer sends a request (2) - With the "PUT" method (3) - to the URL "/fraudcheck" (4) - with the JSON body that * has a field `client.id` that matches a regular expression `[0-9]{10}` * has a field `loanAmount` that is equal to `99999` (5) - with header `Content-Type` equal to `application/json` (6) - then the response will be sent with (7) - status equal `200` (8) - and JSON body equal to { "fraudCheckStatus": "FRAUD", "rejectionReason": "Amount too high" } (9) - with header `Content-Type` equal to `application/json`
From the Producer perspective, in the autogenerated producer-side test:
(1) - A request will be sent to the producer (2) - With the "PUT" method (3) - to the URL "/fraudcheck" (4) - with the JSON body that * has a field `client.id` that will have a generated value that matches a regular expression `[0-9]{10}` * has a field `loanAmount` that is equal to `99999` (5) - with header `Content-Type` equal to `application/json` (6) - then the test will assert if the response has been sent with (7) - status equal `200` (8) - and JSON body equal to { "fraudCheckStatus": "FRAUD", "rejectionReason": "Amount too high" } (9) - with header `Content-Type` matching `application/json.*` */

